article.headline: Nebraska 76, Nebraska-Omaha 62
article.story: LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Aleks Maric, whose appendix were removed 11 days ago, had 29 points and 10 rebounds Tuesday night to lead Nebraska to a 76-62 victory over Nebraska-Omaha in Doc Sadler's regular-season debut as the Cornhuskers' head coach. Jamel White added 18 points for the Huskers, who won their opener for the seventh straight year. Andrew Bridger led the Division II Mavericks with 23 points. Matt Newman had 12 and Michael Jenkins nine for UNO. The game counted as an exhibition for UNO, picked to finish last in the North Central Conference. The Huskers, who lost an exhibition to Division II Southern Illinois-Edwardsville on Saturday, engaged in a choppy game against the Mavericks. The teams combined for 53 fouls and 34 turnovers. The Huskers were in control throughout. After UNO pulled to 33-29, Nebraska went on an 11-3 run the last 4:36 of the half, with Maric's buzzer-beating putback giving the Huskers a 44-32 lead. Maric had five points to key a 9-2 spurt at the start of the second half that upped Nebraska's advantage to 19 points, 53-34. A Bridger 3-pointer pulled the Mavs to 65-53 with 8:08 left, but they would get no closer. Maric, despite having his appendix removed less than two weeks ago, operated at will inside in his 29 minutes of action. He made 11-of-18 shots from the field and 7-of-9 from the free-throw line. Charles Richardson and Sek Henry, who fouled out with 4:17 left, added eight points apiece for the Huskers. Nebraska was missing four players because of injuries. Nine of the 13 players on the roster, in fact, have missed practice time.
